## LC 79 — Word Search

### What is the problem actually asking?

Given a 2D grid of characters and a word, return true if the word exists in the grid by walking through adjacent cells (up, down, left, right). You cannot reuse the same cell in one path.

---

### Core insight: DFS from every cell

The word can start anywhere in the grid. So you try starting from every cell, and from each starting cell you do a DFS trying to match the word character by character.

At each cell you make a choice: go up, down, left, or right. If any direction eventually completes the word, return true.

---

### How is this different from Permutations?

Permutations used a 1D bool[] to track used elements. Here you use a 2D bool[,] used to track which cells are on your current path.

Same idea — mark before recursing, unmark after (backtrack).

---

### Base cases (in order)

1. Out of bounds — return false
2. Cell already used — return false
3. Cell does not match word[index] — return false
4. index == word.Length - 1 AND cell matches — return true (found it!)

---

### After the base cases

Mark the cell as used, then try all 4 directions with index+1. Store the result, unmark the cell (backtrack), return the result.

Why unmark? Because other paths starting from different cells need to be able to use this cell. If you leave it marked from a failed path, future paths will wrongly skip it.

---

### The full solution

```csharp
public bool Exist(char[][] board, string word) {
    int rows = board.Length, cols = board[0].Length;
    bool[,] used = new bool[rows, cols];

    for (int i = 0; i < rows; i++)
        for (int j = 0; j < cols; j++)
            if (backtrack(board, word, used, i, j, 0))
                return true;

    return false;
}

bool backtrack(char[][] board, string word, bool[,] used, int r, int c, int index) {
    if (r < 0 || r >= board.Length || c < 0 || c >= board[0].Length) return false;
    if (used[r, c]) return false;
    if (word[index] != board[r][c]) return false;
    if (index == word.Length - 1) return true;

    used[r, c] = true;

    bool found = backtrack(board, word, used, r-1, c, index+1) ||
                 backtrack(board, word, used, r+1, c, index+1) ||
                 backtrack(board, word, used, r, c-1, index+1) ||
                 backtrack(board, word, used, r, c+1, index+1);

    used[r, c] = false;
    return found;
}
```

---

### Backtracking pattern — same as always

mark → recurse → unmark

The only thing new here is the state is a 2D grid instead of a 1D list.

---

### Complexity

Time: O(m * n * 4^L) where L = word length. Each cell can start a DFS that branches 4 ways at each step.
Space: O(m * n) for the used grid + O(L) call stack depth.
